student_id <-  2023301345
library(tidyverse)
library(data.table)
library(broom) # for tidy statistical summaries
library(caret) # for regression performance measures
library(psych) # for pairwise comparisons
library(car) # for multicollinearity
library(moments) # for higher moments 

library(PearsonDS) # for Pearson distribution
library(rethinking) # for LKJ distribution
set.seed(student_id)
nvar <- 6
sampsize <- 1e3
etax <- 1e-3
train_ratio <- 0.7
matx <- rlkjcorr(1, nvar, etax)
sampx <- rmvnorm(1e3, sigma = matx)
sampx <- pnorm(sampx)
means <- rnorm(nvar)
vars <- rexp(nvar, 1)
kurts <- rexp(nvar, 1) + 3
skews <- (rbeta(nvar, 3, 3) - 0.5)*2
colnamesx <- paste(sample(words, nvar + 1), "1", sep = "")
sampx_dt <- as.data.table(sampx)
sampx_dt <- as.data.table(mapply(function(x, a, b, c, d) qpearson(x, moments = c(a, b, c, d)), sampx_dt,
                                 means, vars, skews, kurts))
paramst <- as.matrix(runif(nvar, -5, 5))
errx <- as.matrix(rnorm(sampsize, 0, sqrt(rexp(1, 0.1))))
responsex <- as.matrix(sampx_dt) %*% paramst + errx
sampx_dt <- cbind(responsex, sampx_dt)
setnames(sampx_dt, colnamesx)
train_indices <- sampx_dt[,sample(.N * train_ratio)]
train_data <- sampx_dt[train_indices]
test_data <- sampx_dt[-train_indices]
normlz <- function(x)
{
    meanr <- mean(x, na.rm = T)
    varr <- var(x, na.rm = T)
    skewr <- skewness(x, na.rm = T)
    kurtr <- kurtosis(x, na.rm = T)
    normlx <- qnorm(ppearson(x, moments = c(meanr, varr, skewr, kurtr)))
    ifelse(is.infinite(normlx), NA, normlx)
    }

R squared value is 0.6316 which means it is not high (0.6316<0.80). That is, our decision variable can be explained by approximately 63% of our variables. Also we should reject the null hypothesis because p value (2.2e-16) is smaller than 0.05. Hence, my model is statistically significant. Describe1,test1,lad1 are significant because they are smaller than 5. Intercept value is -2.3802 which means when we set other variables to zero we get response variable's value by looking at intercept value. Describe1, test1 and mind1 have positive, guess1,lad1,it1 have negative sign.

Describe1 has the highest vif value. Also it1 and describe 1 has vif value higher than 5. Our model shows signs of high multicollinearity.

The variables it1 (VIF = 7.52) and describe1 (VIF = 8.96) have VIF scores are above the common threshold of 5. Hence, they are highly correlated with other predictors in our model.
